sec.p:
Compound extreme temperature‐PM2.5 pollution events can arise from their two‐way interactions associated with multiple mechanisms. First, extreme temperature increases energy consumption and fossil fuel combustion, thereby elevating emissions of PM2.5 precursors (e.g., Volatile Organic Compounds (VOCs), SO2, NO
x
), leading to elevated PM2.5 concentrations (Auffhammer et al., 2017; Wei et al., 2022). Second, higher temperatures increase wildfire risks, releasing large amounts of PM2.5 into the atmosphere (Burke et al., 2023; Childs et al., 2022). Third, extreme heat often coincides with stagnant meteorological conditions, such as high pressure, weak winds, and a shallow boundary layer, which inhibit the dispersion of pollutants and cause PM2.5 to accumulate near the surface (Nasong et al., 2025). In turn, PM2.5 can influence temperature through radiative and dynamic feedbacks (S.‐L. Chen et al., 2021; J. Li et al., 2020; X. Wang et al., 2024). Together, these processes highlight the complex and reciprocal nature of temperature–PM2.5 interactions.

We analyze the differences in frequency and trends of heat + PM2.5 and cold + PM2.5 events by examining PM2.5 under different temperature conditions. Figure S11 in Supporting Information S1 shows the average PM2.5 concentrations in winter (December–February in the Northern Hemisphere; June–August in the Southern Hemisphere) and summer (June–August in the Northern Hemisphere; December–February in the Southern Hemisphere), and we find that PM2.5 concentrations are higher in winter at most global stations. However, this association may reflect a combination of factors such as seasonal emissions, atmospheric stability, and boundary layer dynamics, rather than temperature effects alone. We further explore the PM2.5 concentration distributions under different temperatures across various countries (Figure 4a). We find that PM2.5 concentrations are higher under low‐temperature conditions in China, India, and the EU. The USA exhibits higher PM2.5 concentrations in high‐temperature days, which may be attributed to more frequent wildfire activities during hot weather (Hu et al., 2025). Australia, another wildfire hotspot, similarly shows higher PM2.5 concentrations under high‐temperature conditions, which validates our mechanistic hypothesis regarding the temperature dependence of PM2.5 in the USA (Figure S12 in Supporting Information S1). These distributions exhibit consistent trends across the two PM2.5 data sets. Beyond differences in emission sources, certain atmospheric chemical processes can also explain the concentration differences between low‐ and high‐temperature conditions. At lower temperatures, the gas‐particle partitioning of semi‐volatile species favors the particulate phase, particularly for ammonium nitrate (NH4NO3), which thermodynamically dissociates into gaseous ammonia (NH3) and nitric acid (HNO3) at higher temperatures (M. Wang et al., 2020). Conversely, elevated temperatures enhance photochemical oxidation of VOCs and nitrogen oxides (NO
x
), promoting secondary organic aerosol formation, which can subsequently increase PM2.5 levels through oxidation pathways (Hallquist et al., 2009; Srivastava et al., 2022). However, higher temperatures are also associated with deeper boundary layer heights, which dilute surface‐level pollutant concentrations and may offset the enhanced chemical production (Q. Li et al., 2021). Overall, differences in PM2.5 concentration levels reflect variations in both emission sources and atmospheric chemical processes.
